08561nam a22012255i 9783110931419DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20122005gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831109314197 a10.1515/97831109314192doi  a(DE-B1597)50289  a(OCoLC)979595065  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aHN10.R7bT355 2005eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a937223  aNH 52852rvk0(DE-625)rvk/125680:02aA Tall Order. Writing the Social History of the Ancient World :bEssays in honor of William V. Harris /ced. by Jean-Jacques Aubert, Zsuzsanna Várhelyi.  a1. Aufl. 1aLeipzig : bB. G. Teubner, c[2012] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (379 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeiträge zur Altertumskunde ,x1616-0452 ;v21600ti-iv -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tWilliam V. Harris: The first forty years of scholarship (1965-2005) -- tReligion in context -- tA God of Reciprocity: Torah and Social Relations in an Ancient Mediterranean Society -- tDistinguishing Jewishness in Antiquity -- tJesus, an Adulteress, and the Development of Christian Scripture -- tConstantius II and the First Removal of the Altar of Victory -- t‘Du lard ou du cochon’? The Τestamentum Ρorcelli as a Jewish Anti-Christian Pamphlet -- tImperialism and its soldiers -- tAristocratic Competition, Horses, and the Spolia Opima Once Again -- tAn Architecture of Human Heads: Gallic Responses to Roman Power -- tSoldiers’ Slaves, ‘Dirty Work’, and the Social Status of Roman Soldiers -- tLaw and economy in ancient society -- tVeterans, Agriculture, and Monetization in the Late Roman Republic -- tCountry Villas in Roman Central Italy: Reassessing the Evidence -- tThe Delicts of the Countryside in Longus’ Daphnis and Chloe -- tLocal Governments and Collegia: A New Appraisal of the Evidence -- tHistoriography -- tImagining Olympia: Hippias of Elis and the First Olympic Victor List -- tA Sense of Change and the Historiography of the Turn from Republic to Empire -- tAfterword -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDieser Band erinnert an den 65. Geburtstag von William Vernon Harris (13. September 2003), als eine Gruppe seiner früheren Studenten übereinkam, ihn mit der Herausgabe einer Sammlung von Essays zu ehren, die das breite Spektrum der Interessengebiete und Einflüsse ihres Ratgebers repräsentieren sollten. Die 15 Beiträge rangieren nun chronologisch von der ersten Olympiade bis in die Spätantike und diskutieren verschiedenste Fragen der Weltmachtpolitik, des Rechts, der Wirtschaft und Religion der antiken mediterranen Welt. Gemeinsamer Nenner aller Essays ist die soziale und historische Perspektive, aus der heraus sie viele gängige Ansichten über die Geschichte der Antike in Fragen stellen. Die Autoren der Beiträge sehen sich alle in der Schuld des formenden wissenschaftlichen Scharfsinns ihres Mentors William V. Harris, zusätzlich zu der nicht geringen Anforderung, sich mit seiner Arbeit auseinanderzusetzen.  aThis volume commemorates the 65th birthday of William Vernon Harris (on September 13, 2003), when a group of his former students agreed to honor him with a collection of essays that would represent the wide variety of interests and influences of our advisor and friend. The fifteen papers in fact range chronologically from the first Olympics to late antiquity and discuss various questions of imperialism, law, economy, and religion in the ancient Mediterranean world. The essays share a social historical perspective from which they challenge as many commonly accepted notions in ancient history. The contributors acknowledge their intellectual debt to the formative scholarly acumen of William V. Harris, which adds up to the "tall order" of engaging with his work.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescrip